04447nam a22005535i 9780520926264DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19981998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209262647 a10.1525/97805209262642doi  a(DE-B1597)648132  a(OCoLC)1419789207  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0020002bisacsh1 aTandy, David W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWarriors into Traders :bThe Power of the Market in Early Greece /cDavid W. Tandy; ed. by David W. Tandy. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1998] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (311 p.) :b13 figures, 12 tables, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aClassics and Contemporary Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- tPart One: The Economic Transformation -- t2. More Greeks -- tAppendix A. Snodgrass's Burial Counts -- tAppendix B. Adjustments to Snodgrass's Counts -- tAppendix C. Dedication Patterns on Mt. Hymettus -- tAppendix D. Historical Patterns of Growth and the Greek Numbers -- t3. Early Movements of Goods and of Greeks -- t4. Structure and Change in Dark Age Greece from the Fall of Mycenae through the Homeric Epics -- t5. A Great Transformation -- tPart Two: The Responses -- t6. Tools of Exclusion -- t7. Epic and Other Memories -- t8. Response from the Periphery -- t9. Conclusions -- tBibliography -- tSubject Index -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe eighth century dawned on a Greek world that had remained substantially unchanged during the centuries of stagnation known as the Dark Age. This book is a study of the economic and cultural upheaval that shook mainland Greece and the Aegean area in the eighth century, and the role that poetry played in this upheaval. Using tools from political and economic anthropology, David Tandy argues that between about 800 and 700 B.C., a great transformation of dominant economic institutions took place involving wrenching adjustments in the way status and wealth were distributed within the Greek communities.Tandy explores the economic organization of preindustrial societies, both ancient and contemporary, to shed light on the Greek experience. He argues that the sudden shift in Greek economic formations led to new social behaviors and to new social structures such as the polis, itself a by-product of economic change. Unraveling the dialectic between the material record and epic poetry, Tandy shows that the epic tradition mirrored these new social behaviors and that it portrayed the stresses that economic change brought to the ancient Aegean world.Tandy brings in comparative evidence from other small-scale communities beset by changes, spotlighting the specific plight of one community, Ascra in Boeotia, on whose behalf Hesiod sang his Works and Days. The result is a lively, moving account of a human dilemma that, many centuries later, is all too familiar.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAncient. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aTandy, David W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052022691340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092626440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520926264423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520926264/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles